rness as the condition of possibility of the two concepts, Xu argues that one legacy of the Jesuit-Confucian encounter has been the shared recognition that cultural differences are what both motivated and conditioned cross-cultural exchanges and understandings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChristianity and other religionsxConfucianism. 0aConfucianismxRelationsxCatholicism. 0aConfucianismzChinaxHistory. 0aHospitalityzChina. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Comparative Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : History of Religion. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2021z978311149169140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848496940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438484969423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438484969/original  a978-3-11-149169-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles